title: Airsoft Trigger for Version 2 (V2) Gearbox AEGs and HPA systems *Re-Upload*

description.text:
Tweaked version of my previously uploaded model, it should now work in standard AEG airsoft guns. Depending on your brand/model you may need to perform some slight modification/filing for proper fitment and function.

Print at as high of a fill density as you can manage (80% minimum, 90-100% recommended) and be careful with your temperatures, the "spur" on the top is quite thin and will warp under the heat of the nozzle if your settings are too hot or if your cooling fan isn't doing its job.

  1. Pick the appearance you'd like (triggers are incredibly low stress in AEGs so strength shouldn't be an issue)
  2. Flatten and orient the model (I suggest cura), then scale to 102% (X & Y, leave Z at 100%) to account for material shrinkage
  3. Print
  4. Use a 1/8" (~3mm) drill bit to ream out the pivot hole
  5. Cut a length of 1/8" (~3mm) brass rod (or use a broken 1/8" drill bit, m3 bolt or similar sized shaft/rod) and glue it into the trigger body to act as the pivot pin (approximately 28mm long, may need to be slightly shorter or longer in some gearbox cases)
  6. Test fit into gearbox and check function, perform any fine-tuning modifications needed

Feel free to modify the design to your liking, but remember that some features are necessary for function and are not simply aesthetic. The small 1mm x 10mm slot on the back for example is absolutely necessary for the trigger spring to index into, without it you're going to have to drill/melt a hole for the trigger spring to fit.
The main lightening cut (ie. the "hollow" part in the center of the main trigger body) is purely aesthetic, so whatever crazy designs you want will likely work out just fine. AEG triggers don't experience much stress in use (unless they jam or get stuck), so unless you make the edges incredibly thin (2mm or less) you likely won't have any structural issues.

I had originally designed this model for use with a CNC mill, so they should work well regardless of whether you're planning on 3d printing or utilizing reductive manufacturing techniques (ie. CNC milling).

DISCLAIMERS!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
-DO NOT expect this to sound good
-This is a proof of concept, not a working instrument
-The strings will break with any rough playing
-I only have a printer with a 5 inch print bed, so I designed it with that in mind. Ideally, it should be re-designed and printed with a larger printer
-The holes are for pins in case you wanted to attach real strings (metal, nylon, gut, etc, not PLA) to the soundboard
-I only know that this works with PLA. I can't speak for ABS or other materials
-This is a WORK IN PROGRESS. I can already think of innumerable improvements to the design (like thinner walls), so hang tight for improvements

This is a 100% 3D printed harp instrument. The main body prints in one piece, strings and all. Then you just have to glue on a soundboard and glue together a crimping mechanism that keeps the strings taut. The crimping mechanism attaches to the body just by pressure, but you need to glue together the two gears and tuning bar. Once that's together, pop on the crimping mechanism and then start strumming (but please strum softly so the strings last longer).

I like to build musical instruments, and thus often find myself testing out the musical properties of various materials. One day I was changing a spool of filament, and my printer started eeking out a ton of thin, stringy PLA. Naturally, I tried stretching some of it across a soundbox (read, a cardboard box). Lo and behold, it actually worked! It could be plucked and made a sound just like any other cheap string material. The string didn't last very long before breaking, but it worked for a brief time.

So I got to work designing and printing small prototype harps and finding out the right dimensions for my printer to print suspended strings across a gap. Since I wanted the strings to print onto the soundbox in one print (without requiring glue), I decided to tune the harp using a crimping mechanism instead of standard tuning pins.

Don't ask me what the tuning for this is because it would be futile to attempt to work out a tuning. The PLA just wouldn't take to being tuned like a more suitable material (like high carbon steel) would. And the stings are so small that the pitch is unpleasantly high and tinny, so tuning doesn't much matter anyway. The crimping mechanism only serves to get the strings taut, not to get them tuned. I wonder if it's possible to print suspended strings and then print a few more layers over them to make the strings thicker, but I doubt it, and I haven't tested it yet.

This is really just a fun proof of concept project, or something to use for decoration, so please don't expect a nice instrument from this print. It would be a far better idea to print a base and then attach real strings to it, rather than using plastic. I just wanted to show that a working harp could be 100% printed from PLA, strings and all.

Please, please, please feel free to take this concept and run with it. I'd love to see what others can make using PLA strings.

title: Upgraded Max Z Effector (Inductive Sensor, 30mm Fan and 30mm Blower/Part Cooling)

description.text:
Description: The JAW Effector improves print quality by raising the hotend nozzle closer to the plain of the effector's arms. This isn't a unique idea, but my design is smaller in diameter than other designs that utilize ball ends. The result of this compact effector is improved print accuracy, while still maintaining the original build volume of a Kossel style delta printer.

Testing: Final design tested 2/27/18 without any clearance issues on my homebrew Kossel Mini delta printer using Traxxis rod ends. Works like a charm!

Hints for assembling perfect traxxis rod ends: First, glue the carbon rods to the rod ends using a printable jig found on Thingiverse. Then, hold the rod ends in a shallow pot of water at a rolling boil. After submerging the rods for 10 to 15 seconds, squeeze the circular holes gently with pliers (they should bend under pressure and seem to return after you stop squeezing). Next, push the balls into the rod ends (make sure to do this on the correct side of the rod ends, one side has a larger lip and the other has a shiny ring around the opening). If done properly, you will have zero play in your effector's arms 100% of the time (no throwing out ball ends that are loose after assembly). If you assemble a ball end that isn't tight, gently remove the ball from the rod end and repeat the assembly process again to correct the issue.

Print Settings:
-Print in PETG (or you can use ABS). Regular PLA will not withstand the higher temperatures around the heater block.

-Print with supports for the main body of the effector (under the radius/curve of the hotend arms so they print well and to support the center column of the effector where the hotend will go. The hotend clip will not need support.

Hardware:
-You will use various M3 bolts and will also need an extra m3 nut (besides the 12 for the effector's arms) for the inductive sensor holder.

-The effector is designed to be used with one 30x30x10 axial fan to cool the hotend, as well as one 30x30x10 radial fan for print/part cooling. (You can find these on eBay and sometimes on Amazon when they are in stock. They are 5-volt fans, which is perfect for a Duet board).

description.text: Monster Hunter Airou cat head

UPDATED 2017-12-20: Now includes a working 1.1.7 binary, as well as the older releases previously published here.

Wanted to update the firmware on my stock Malyan M150, only to find lots of online commentary, but no binaries. My primary motivation was to enable fail-safe features missing from the factory, and to resolve general annoyances.

  • The minimum temperature feature has been enabled, to prevent thermal runaway.
  • The maximum temperature(s) have been increased; hot-end 275˚C, heat-bed 115˚C.
  • X, Y, and Z limits have been set to optimal values (206 x 220 x 170).
  • The encoder switch has an improved response to movement.

Sources:

  • Marlin Github Repository
  • How to Configure Arduino for the Melzi Board
  • Modifications to work with the Non-standard Melzi Board.

Many thanks to the Marlin developers, and the French RepRap community. I've included the source also if you have your own configuration requirements.

Windows
  1. Unzip the files in a convenient location.
  2. Install the included CH341 USB Drivers.
  3. Connect the Malyan M150 via the USB cable.
  4. Power on the Malyan M150 while holding down the selection/encode switch.
    The display should be intentionally blank, if not, try again.
  5. Run flash.cmd - if it exits without showing progress first, edit the flash.cmd with the correct COM number. This can be found in the windows device manager.
  6. When complete, switch the Malyan M150 off, then back on.
Linux
  1. Unzip the files.
  2. Install required packages.
    sudo apt-get update
     sudo apt-get install avrdude
  3. Flash the Malyan M150.
    avrdude -v -p atmega1284p -c arduino -P /dev/ttyUSB0 -b 57600 -V -U flash:w:marlin-1.1.7.hex
Repeat as directed; but use the marlin-1.0.0.hex firmware included, instead.

description.text:
I think the whole fidget spinner thing is corny, but my kids are into them right now. I had a set of bearings on my desk, and for whatever reason I found myself spinning them as I work. So I gave in and designed my own, but I just wanted a disk. Nothing fancy.

This design uses pennies for perimeter weighting, because you can't get much cheaper than 12 cents for weights vs. $1 or so for three cheap bearings. The center bearing is a typical 608.

I also didn't like most of the caps I found, so I designed some simple ones that press together and are quite thin. I made sure there was enough of a shoulder on it to keep the cap from rubbing on the bearing surfaces.

The outside of the disc spinner also features some nice knurling, so it's easy to spin fast.

The pictured print is out of Onyx, 50% fill, and 0.1mm Z resolution.

Enjoy!

title: Parametric paint shelves for Clarke CWR50 Metal Tool Board

description.text:
Simple 3D scad model for the Clarke CWR50 tool board - to hold small paint tubes. The shelves are angled back a little, so the tubes won't fall off. With some minor modifications I guess it would be useful for small tools etc as well.

The design is fully parametric, and you can specify the number of hook perforations wide you want the shelf to be (num), the size (paint_slot_width) and spacing (paint_slot_spacing) between the centres of the paint slots. The scad code will then squeeze in as many as possible.

See https://www.sodnpoo.com/posts.xml/parametric_paint_shelf_for_clarke_cwr50_metal_tool_board.xml for more information.

title: Encoder Wheel with two rows of 48 slits

description.text:
This encoder is parametrized. It is written in OpenSCAD.

It has two stripes near the edge. Each has 48 slits. Both strips are aligned asymmetrically to produce different phase-lag when wheel rotates in different directions. Moreover the open and close area of each strip are not equal to each other. This might help in increasing the noise-margin if you are using optical or infra-red LED/Diode pair to detect opening and closing (1 and 0). If you are using IR photo-diode, make sure that LED is not strong enough to penetrate the wheel.

I hope that this design is better suited to detect both speed and direction. If you are only interested in measuring speed, use any of the strip.

title: yacs three arm compact coin spinner

description.text:
Yet another coin fidget spinner. This one is a compact three arm version. My personal favourite of the bunch.

The centre hole is for the standard 608 skate bearing, 22 mm × 7 mm.

There are several ready-made STLs there, for coins i had lying around:

  • Nine 20 eurocent coins
  • Twelve 5 eurocent coins
  • Twelve 1 eurocent coins
  • Nine UK 2p coins
  • Twelve UK pennies
  • Twelve 1 角人民币 (1 Jiao RMB) coins
  • Twelve 50 eurocent coins (For this one you have to set the coins/arm by hand. Also, the image shows it rotated by 90°, but it works OK in slic3r anyway.)

The 1 eurocent version is somewhat smaller than the other ones, with thin wall between the bearing and the coins, and an thinner outer wall, compared to the other STLs.

This is slightly parametric. Whit a bit of work you can use your favourite coins, either local currencies, or parts of that little pile of foreign currency that travellers tend to collect. For that i have included the FreeCAD files. They include a spreadsheet called “sizes”. To get a new spinner, do this:

  • Download FreeCAD and get it running
  • Load the yaccs_3_arm.fcstd FreeCAD file
  • In the tree view, double click on “Sizes”. You should see the spreadsheet
  • Measure your coin or look up its size (Wikipedia, search engine, &c.)
  • Put in the diameter and thickness in B6 and B7. Make sure to keep the = and mm.
  • Check that you have enough coins. The spreadsheet shows the number needed. Typically 12, 9 for thicker coins like 10 eurocent and up.
  • Change other values in the “B” column, to taste.
  • Go back to the yaccs_3_arm view
  • Check that the shown shape looks OK. There are view controls at the top
  • Check that in the tree view there are no exclamation marks as warnings
  • If the spinner looks good, select the last item, “spinner”. It should turn green in the main view.
  • If not, it’s easiest to close without saving and to try again. Change fewer values, and only by small amounts.
  • Look for the dropdown in the tool bar and select “Mesh Design”
  • You should now have a “Meshes” menu. Select “Create mesh from shape …”
  • I have to select the “Standard” radio button. “Mefisto” produces empty meshes.
  • Click OK
  • There should be a “spinner (Meshed)” item in the tree view. Select it.
  • Click on the “Export a mesh to file” icon, enter a file name, select file type (STL or OBJ) and name and click “OK”,
  • Et voilà, you’re done. You have finished your first FreeCAD lesson and can now go ahead and slice and print your customized spinner.

The FreeCAD version is for the more compact (thin walled) version.
I also redesigned this internally, so that changing the sizes should work a little better.

There is also some design history available at my github repo.

title: BMW AGR EGR Cooler Valve Hack Diesel N47N
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a very specific BMW Diesel Engine "Thing". Actually I made it for my BMW 320D E91 LCI (2011) with the N47N Engine. This diesel engine is equipped with an EGR System as well as with an EGR cooling system. Unfortunately the EGR Cooler leads to an annoying tick-tick noise if it will be activated. The EGR Cooler is btw also equipped with an by-pass during the warm up phase until the cooling water has reached 60°C. Afterwards the cooler will be activated by an valve. This valve/regulator will be controlled by an vacuum switch. If you bypass the vacuum switch you will ensure that the EGR cooler will never be active because the vacuum will open the EGR bypass constantly. BTW, over 2800 RPM the the EGR Cooler is never be active and the EGR cooler bypass is active. So actually you just change the part load behavior. The EGR valve itself will still work.
The Thing here will be click in the EGR Cooler bypass switch and hold the hose connector which will bypass the switch. The small plugs are for closing the vacuum switch connections to prevent dirty to get insert. Just use shrink hose and these plugs. By this it is ensured that you can easily rebuild the mod the standard config, Hope that makes sense for you ;) ....you will find more information in terms of this mod by using google or so. The engine cannot be damaged by this mod, but for sure any mod will be done on your own risk and this mod is just for testing purposes because the NOx of your engine will be increased during part load operation.

75 mm dia circular spinner with twelve holes at the rim for 1/2" chrome steel ball bearings (slingshot ammo). Standard 608 skate bearing (8x22x7mm). Scale as necessary for a tight press fit for the balls. Adhesive will throw off the balance. (Just a thought: You might even try 50 caliber lead balls used by muzzleloaders.)

Scale Bearing_Button_v1.stl to 99% so you don't have to press fit it. It's tough to remove the grips from the bearing printed full size.

Try printing with three perimeters, a 20% hex infill, and zero top and bottom layers. This will expose the hex infill (as in the photo), which you use a soda straw to blow against to accelerate the spin. Human power only! DO NOT use an air compressor! Ask your science teacher about centrifugal force.

Using a kerosene-lubed Yellow Jacket ceramic bearing, and with all twelve 1/2" balls installed, I got a five and a half minute spin.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/kOjbeE1PfJq

Make it spin longer!

Set up your fidget to spin as flat and wobble free as possible. Press the 1/2" balls to an equal depth in all the holes, ideally to the center. (Stop printing about 1/3 to 1/2 way through for a handy spacer.) Every bit of wobble steals energy from a gyroscope, so for the longest spins hold it flat and steady down on a tabletop.

Noise also indicates energy loss in a gyroscope. It takes energy to make noise, so the more quietly you spin, the longer you'll spin. Try flipping the spinner over, or spin it backwards, to see if it runs more quietly.

And don't fidget.

description.text:
Switch the unit on and the red light starts glowing. Push the button and the red led is switched off for a random time. As soon as that random time (1 to 5 seconds) is over. the red led goes on again and you have to push as quickly as you can. The reaction time is measured and translated in a color of the RGBcc led.
Blue (<50ms): You are O.K.
Green (100ms): Stop drinking beer.
Red (200ms): Call a cab and don't drive a car until tomorrow.
Flashing red (500ms): Have another beer, it is too late for you anyway.
But remember, this is just a toy.
An Arduino sketch for ATtiny could look like this:

//ReactionTime
int Red = 4; int R = 2; int G = 1; int B = 0; int buttonpin = 4; int x;
int duration; int randtime; int Val;
void setup() {
pinMode(Red, OUTPUT); pinMode(R, OUTPUT); pinMode(G, OUTPUT); pinMode(B, OUTPUT); pinMode(buttonpin, INPUT);
}
void loop() {
digitalWrite(Red,HIGH);
int randtime = random(50,500);
Val = digitalRead(buttonpin);
if(Val == LOW){digitalWrite(Red, LOW);}
delay(randtime);
digitalWrite(Red, HIGH);
duration = pulseIn(buttonpin, HIGH);
if(duration < 10){digitalWrite(B, HIGH);}
if (duration >10 && duration<50){digitalWrite(G, HIGH);}
if (duration >50 && duration<100){digitalWrite(R, HIGH);}
if (duration >100) {
for(x=0;x<10;x++){
digitalWrite(R,HIGH);delay(100);digitalWrite(R, LOW);}}
}

Just a couple of modifiers to give Honeycomb vase(by radus) more stable bottom. Also i think it looks more organic. Done in Blender 3d, .blend file is attached.

[sotvl_Spiral-Vase.stl] is a solid shape. you should print it in "Spiralize Contour"(Cura) or "Spiral Vase"(Slic3r). Ts is not waterproof, as it will be small holes on a way up from bottom. So, it is not good for water, but soil is ok.

[sotvl_thick 1,2mm] - with a proper thickness calculation. 1mm and 2mm thick respectfully. probably waterproof... but not tested by myself with a print yet. Slice and print as a usual thing, not in vase mode.

[sotvl_thick-Blender.stl] is thick/thin shape. should be ok for usual print and waterproof, but need more testing with prints. At current state, it seems it less reliable compared to sotvlthick 1,2mm.

[sotvl.blend] - source Blender3d file, shape and thickness can be changed there. (for advanced users)

description.text:
I modified the beautiful project Clasp for stick it to the wall.
The thing is very hard to print, you have 3 options:

1) print the full hand vertically. This option is the better for the skin quality, but the support structures tend to collapse, You have to create special cylinders to support the parts.

2) print the full hand horizontally. With this option you have to work very hard for detach support structures. You need a consistent post production phase like sanding.

3) Cut the hand into two parts using netfab (file ClaspHand1 and ClaspHand2) and after printing, paste the parts with a strong adhesive such as E6000. With this option is very simple to detach the support structures, specially those that block the hole through which the electric wire must pass. I stuffed the fracture line with "sugru pasta".

The thing was coated with epoxy resin like XTC-3D.
In picture 3 (blu hand, printed in two parts) you can see the fracture line, whereas in picture 4 (red hand, printed in only one part) the result is better.
Use a nice bulb holder and a nice led bulb, like Philips classic (see pictures).
If you print ClaspHand1 rotate it 180°.
WallSupport1 and WallSupport2 are glued with E6000.
WallSupport2 is printed in Laywood.

With that in mind I 3D Printed a mount that clipped onto the Mavic Pro battery pack. The camera will be attached by a M4 camera screw.

You can check out the video effect on:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IaRhsfx_z8s
I've take a short clip with my Theta S attached onto it. Enjoy. (And forgive me for the crappy print quality)

The design is based on the DJI Mavic Pro Universal Support posted on the link:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2137716

Building notes:

  1. Requires M4 camera screw (the tripod screw)
  2. I made the hole with minimum clearance with the M4 screw. So when you screw it in it should be real hard. But will prevent the unit from shaking in flight (Especially for Theta S since it is a tall "rod")
  3. Should be good for GoPro with a correct adapter mount
  4. Support may be required for 3D printing

Flight notes:

  1. The upward clearance sensor/compass seems to be interfered with the Theta S on-board
    -Be sure you check for surroundings before flight
    -Make sure you do it in daytime and monitor the on-board camera for Mavic's whereabout
  2. For the first flight it is advised you to do a low attitude test flight and get familiar with the control
  3. With additional weight onboard, it is advised you don't push the limit (battery/attitude, etc). Always check the location and status of the drone and maintain a good line of sight!
  4. Do it at your own risk :D! It is important you take care of your drone!
